This domain addresses philosophical arguments against the valorization of self-reliance and doing-it-yourself (DIY). The literature reveals three major critical perspectives. First, the division of cognitive labor literature (Kitcher, Alexander et al.) argues that specialization and reliance on experts is epistemically superior to individual self-sufficiency in complex knowledge domains. Second, the epistemic dependence literature (Nguyen, Buzzell & Rini, Carter) shows that attempting epistemic self-reliance is often impossible or counterproductive given our cognitive limitations and the structure of modern knowledge. Third, work on delegation and outsourcing (Fisher & Oppenheimer, Ahlstrom-Vij) demonstrates how reliance on others can be both efficient and epistemically virtuous when done appropriately.

