  RELEVANCE: Stoljar's substantive account raises questions about whether social norms that valorize either DIY activities or delegation might affect autonomy. If preferences for doing things oneself are shaped by oppressive norms of self-reliance that prevent people from accepting help, those preferences might be non-autonomous. Conversely, if preferences for delegation are shaped by norms that denigrate manual labor or practical skills, those preferences might also be non-autonomous.

  POSITION: Substantive relational autonomy—autonomy requires normative competence not damaged by oppression.
  },
  keywords = {autonomy, substantive-autonomy, feminist-philosophy, Medium},
  abstract = {Abstract This paper reconstructs Van Parijs’ core argument for an unconditional basic income and presents three objections against it. The first and most theoretical objection attacks the egalitarian basis of Van Parijs’ argument and suggests an alternative, humanitarian theory of justice. The second and third more concrete objections accuse Van Parijs of selling-out the right to work as well as the right to recognition of work, for example of family work. The conclusion drawn from these three objections, however, is not that an unconditional basic income cannot be defended. Instead the paper ends by indicating an alternative, humanitarian argument for an unconditional basic income.},
