  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Reconstructs authenticity as a new ideal of universal validity based on "exemplary uniqueness" rather than generalizability. Against both expressivist authenticity (mere self-expression) and rationalist universalism, Ferrara argues authenticity involves "self-congruency" of identity and can ground normative validity through its exemplary character. This provides a pluralism-friendly universalism suited to contemporary diverse societies.

  RELEVANCE: Offers sophisticated reconstruction of authenticity as normative ideal that avoids both subjectivism and rigid universalism. For DIY ethics, Ferrara's account suggests doing things yourself matters when it expresses self-congruent identity in exemplary ways—not just any self-directed action, but those that achieve genuine integration of identity. The emphasis on self-congruency (not mere self-expression) raises questions about when delegation threatens authenticity and when it's compatible with it.

