irtue of her being associated or related to the principal agent is certain ways. Mellema illustrates the idea of moral taint with an example case taken from Kutz (2000, pp. 163–164). The case involves a pacifist employee who works on a project for the United States Department of Defense. According to Mellema, the},
  abstract_source = {s2},
}

@article{stamatiou2024two,
  author = {Stamatiou, Filippos},
  title = {Two Faces of Control for Moral Responsibility},
  journal = {South African Journal of Philosophy},
  year = {2024},
  volume = {43},
  number = {2},
  pages = {202--216},
  doi = {10.1080/02580136.2024.2355011},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Stamatiou distinguishes two aspects of control necessary for moral responsibility: choice (selecting among alternatives) and agenthood (the agent's causal efficacy in bringing about the choice). He argues that both aspects can be realized by human psychology, defending control-based theories against empirical challenges from neuroscience and conceptual worries about the disappearance of the agent in psychological explanations.

  RELEVANCE: Provides a framework for distinguishing control retained in delegation from control relinquished. When one delegates, one may retain choice control (selecting the delegate and goal) while relinquishing agenthood control (the causal process bringing about the outcome). This distinction may matter for assessing the moral significance of personal versus delegated action.

  POSITION: Defends two-component control theory; argues psychological accounts preserve both choice and agenthood.
  },
  keywords = {control, agency, choice, Low},
  abstract = {Control is typically accepted as a necessary condition for moral responsibility. Thus, humans are morally responsible for their actions only if we can realise the right kind of control. Are there good reasons to think that humans can psychologically realise control? This paper is an attempt to address this question by establishing choice and agenthood as separate but interconnected aspects of control. I consider two challenges to the claim that humans can realise the kind of control required for moral responsibility. First, an empirical challenge from cognitive neuroscience provides a familiar way to argue against the realisation of the choice aspect by human psychology. Second, a more formidable conceptual challenge to the aspect of agenthood presents us with scepticism about the kind of explanations that psychology can provide. The second challenge suggests that, in psychological accounts of choice, the agent disappears. Drawing on recent empirical models of cognitive control and philosophical accounts of agency, I conclude that the psychological explanation of choice is consistent with the aspect of agenthood being realised by human psychology.},
  abstract_source = {s2},
}

@article{winckler2025range,
  author = {Winckler-Olick, Hannah},
  title = {The Range of Moral Responsibility: A Beauvoirian Model},
  journal = {European Journal of Philosophy},
  year = {2025},
  doi = {10.1111/ejop.70023},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Drawing on Simone de Beauvoir, Winckler-Olick argues that our responsibility extends beyond consequences we directly cause to include contributions our actions make to shared public values. She proposes an "Extended Range View" under which agents are responsible for shaping the evaluative landscape through their actions, thereby sharing responsibility for the free actions of others who navigate that landscape.

  RELEVANCE: Suggests a novel dimension of responsibility relevant to delegation: when one delegates, one not only distributes causal responsibility but also shapes public values about the acceptability of delegation itself. If delegation becomes a widespread practice, it may alter the evaluative landscape in ways that affect everyone's options and values. This extends responsibility beyond individual delegation decisions.

  POSITION: Extended range view of responsibility; responsibility for contributions to shared values.
  },
  keywords = {moral-responsibility, shared-values, Beauvoir, Low},
  abstract = {In this paper, I propose a view that extends the range of our core agency to include contributions our actions make to public values. This Extended Range View takes seriously Simone de Beauvoir's suggestion that values are not merely handed to us but created and shaped together by our actions. If we properly appreciate the moral weight of our contributions to the value systems that we all engage in—what I will call our evaluative landscape—then we can explain how we can be responsible for the free actions of others. This view significantly extends what we will need to think of as our responsibility (though not to a fully unrestricted range). I will also suggest, however, that we accept a pluralist view about responsibility on which the way that we take responsibility and hold agents responsible for these kinds of value‐based contributions is different from the standard responsibility practices like blame, punishment, and guilt.},
  abstract_source = {s2},
}

@article{gorman2024against,
  author = {Gorman, August},
  title = {Against Neuronormativity in Moral Responsibility},
  journal = {Feminist Philosophy Quarterly},
  year = {2024},
  volume = {10},
  number = {1},
  doi = {10.5206/fpq/2024.1/2.18721},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Gorman critiques the moral responsibility literature's reliance on implicit assumptions about "ideal" or "normal" agency, arguing this imports unjustified normative assumptions that misconstrue agential diversity. She traces the problem to two factors: searching for fundamental agential capacities and systemic discrimination toward psychological variance. A neurodiversity perspective reveals domains of inquiry obscured by neuronormative paradigms.

  RELEVANCE: Challenges standard assumptions about agency that underlie responsibility attributions, including in delegation contexts. If theories of responsibility implicitly assume neurotypical agency, they may mischaracterize the moral significance of delegating tasks to neurodiverse agents or of neurodiverse individuals choosing to delegate. Normative assumptions about "ideal" agency may obscure legitimate reasons for delegation.

  POSITION: Critiques neuronormativity in agency theories; advocates neurodiversity perspective on responsibility.
  },
  keywords = {moral-responsibility, neurodiversity, agency, Low},
  abstract = {The moral responsibility literature frequently relies on both explicit and implicit claims about “ideal” or “normal” agency that import unjustified normative assumptions into our theorizing. In doing so, it both fails to reckon with and misconstrues the reality of agential diversity. In this article I diagnose the root of this problem, which I trace back to the confluence of two factors: the search for fundamental agential capacities, and systemic discrimination toward psychological variance. I then preview three socially and politically important domains of inquiry that have been obscured by this paradigm as a way of motivating the need for and value of applying a neurodiversity perspective to moral responsibility and the ethics of blame.},
  abstract_source = {s2},
}

@article{sartorio2025agency,
  author = {Sartorio, Carolina},
  title = {Agency and Responsibility in Criminal Law},
  journal = {Criminal Law and Philosophy},
  year = {2025},
  doi = {10.1007/s11572-025-09756-9},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Sartorio examines the relationship between agency and responsibility in criminal law contexts, focusing on how legal doctrines of actus reus and mens rea track philosophical concepts of agency and control. She argues that criminal responsibility requires not just causation but a specific form of agency: the defendant's action must flow from their practical reasoning in ways that make the outcome attributable to them.

  RELEVANCE: Provides legal-philosophical resources for thinking about responsibility in delegation contexts. Criminal law's doctrines of complicity and conspiracy offer frameworks for assessing when delegating tasks to others generates criminal liability. The actus reus requirement (voluntary act) may illuminate when delegation preserves versus severs the connection between principal and outcome.

  POSITION: Agency-based account of criminal responsibility; emphasizes attributability.
  },
  keywords = {agency, criminal-law, attributability, Medium},
  abstract = {Abstract In Fundamentals of Criminal Law: Responsibility, Culpability, and Wrongdoing, Simester notes that one of the basic principles of criminal law is the idea that criminal liability requires, at a minimum, moral responsibility: defendants cannot be criminally liable for something unless they are morally responsible for it. For example, we cannot be held liable for harmful consequences of involuntary behaviors such as muscle spasms, reflexes, seizures, episodes of sleepwalking, etc., for which we are not morally responsible. Simester embraces this basic assumption; however, he also challenges some standard assumptions about moral responsibility itself—in particular, he challenges the standard way of understanding the relationship between moral responsibility, voluntariness, and agency—and argues for an alternative view. This paper is a critical examination of Simester’s arguments and thoughts on this important topic. I pinpoint some ways in which I think his arguments are on target, and other ways in which I think they might not be. Where it helps illuminate the discussion, I draw connections with the philosophy of action and moral responsibility literatures.},
  abstract_source = {openalex},
}

@article{clarkChalmers1998extended,
  author = {Clark, Andy and Chalmers, David J.},
  title = {The Extended Mind},
  journal = {Analysis},
  year = {1998},
  volume = {58},
  number = {1},
  pages = {7--19},
  doi = {10.1093/analys/58.1.7},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Cognitive processes can literally extend beyond the brain and skull to include environmental resources. When an external tool (like Otto's notebook) is reliably available, functionally integrated, and automatically endorsed, it constitutes part of the cognitive system rather than merely supporting it. Active externalism differs from semantic externalism by focusing on how the environment drives cognitive processes.

  RELEVANCE: Foundational for understanding whether tool use extends the self or delegates tasks externally. If tools extend cognition, then using technology doesn't outsource tasks to something other than the self—it reconfigures the boundaries of the cognitive agent. This challenges the DIY question's assumption that tool use differs categorically from doing things oneself. The parity principle (if external process plays same functional role as internal, it's cognitive) bears on whether using AI differs from human delegation.

  POSITION: Extended mind optimism—environmental resources can constitute cognition when properly integrated.
  },
  keywords = {extended-mind, foundational, tool-use, High},
  abstract = {Where does the mind stop and the rest of the world begin? The question invites two standard replies. Some accept the intuitive demarcations of skin and skull, and say that what is outside the body is outside the mind. Others are impressed by arguments suggesting that the meaning of our words "just ain't in the head", and hold that this externalism about meaning carries over into an externalism about mind. We propose to pursue a third position. We will advocate an externalism about mind, but one that is in no way grounded in the debatable role of external reference in fixing the contents of our mental states. Rather, we advocate an *active externalism*, based on the active role of the environment in driving cognitive processes.},
  abstract_source = {s2},
}

@article{brittenNeish2025cognitive,
  author = {Britten-Neish, George},
  title = {Cognitive offloading and the causal structure of human action},
  journal = {Synthese},
  year = {2025},
  volume = {205},
  number = {2},
  doi = {10.1007/s11229-024-04887-3},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Cognitive offloading is paradigmatically intentional action, yet debates about extended cognition ignore this fact. Opposition to extended cognition stems partly from unarticulated intuitions about agency rooted in Davidson's interface model (intentions cause bodily movements). An Anscombean model of action—where actions express intentions only within appropriate teleologically structured contexts—better supports extended cognition by recognizing agency's general dependence on bodily and environmental settings.

  RELEVANCE: Directly addresses how action theory shapes views of cognitive offloading. If offloading is genuine action (not mere causal enablement), then delegating to tools is doing something oneself in a different form. This challenges views that treat tool use as diminishing agency. The Anscombean framework suggests that doing things yourself doesn't require keeping all processes internal—what matters is the teleological structure integrating agent, body, and environment. Illuminates DIY questions about when using tools counts as doing it yourself.

  POSITION: Extended mind proponent using Anscombean action theory to defend cognitive offloading as genuine agency.
  },
  keywords = {extended-mind, cognitive-offloading, action-theory, agency, High},
  abstract = {The hypothesis of extended cognition (HEC) casts human cognition as constitutively dependent on its bodily and environmental context. Drawing on recent empirical work on ‘cognitive offloading’, HEC’s defenders claim that information processing offloaded onto such brain-external resources is sometimes ‘genuinely’ cognitive. But while debates about offloading have a high profile in philosophy of cognitive science, surprisingly little attention has been paid to the fact that paradigm cases of offloading are intentional actions. As a result, opposition to HEC is driven in part by unarticulated intuitions about the metaphysics of human agency. Thinking of action as a kind of interface between separately constituted intentions and bodily movements can make HEC look problematic. But while this view of agency has been popularised – most prominently by Donald Davidson – as analytic philosophy of action’s ‘standard story’, it has come under pressure from philosophers influenced by Elizabeth Anscombe’s very different account. According to this, actions express an agent’s intention only in so far as they fit into the right kind teleologically structured worldly context. In this paper, I’ll argue that HEC’s supporters should adopt an Anscombean model of action. That is, they should understand cognitive offloading as a manifestation of human agency’s general dependence on its bodily and environmental setting.},
  abstract_source = {s2},
}

