  RELEVANCE: Applies extended mind debates to education and autonomy. Distinguishes between efficiency gains from offloading and autonomy costs from overdependence. Relevant to DIY questions because it identifies when delegation (even to tools) diminishes valuable capacities. The "freedom to achieve" framework suggests that what matters morally about doing things yourself isn't just the outcome but the preserved capacity for independent achievement. Challenges pure consequentialist defenses of technological delegation.

