  RELEVANCE: Arneson's skepticism about meaningful work as a justice requirement provides a counterpoint to Veltman, Moriarty, and others. If meaningful work is not required by justice, delegation choices are primarily matters of personal preference or prudence, not moral obligation. This would make DIY supererogatory (valuable but not required) rather than morally significant. Relevant for determining whether moral value of doing things yourself has political implications or is purely personal.

