  CORE ARGUMENT: Analyzes Marx's conception of self-realization through work, distinguishing several components: exercising capacities, developing new capacities, and seeing oneself in one's products. Questions whether work is the best arena for self-realization compared to politics, art, or science. Notes tension between self-realization (developing oneself) and social contribution (serving others). Market constraints and division of labor make comprehensive self-realization through work unlikely even in non-capitalist systems.

